        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Interest Rate Modeling: The Need for Stochastic Models\n",
        "\n",
        "### Limitations of Deterministic Models\n",
        "\n",
        "Traditional approaches that assume constant interest rates are unrealistic because:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Empirical Evidence**: Interest rates exhibit mean reversion—they fluctuate but gravitates toward long-term averages\n",
        "2. **Volatility**: Rates can change unexpectedly due to economic shocks, policy changes, or changing market expectations\n",
        "3. **Path-Dependency**: The sequence of rate changes matters for path-dependent derivatives\n",
        "4. **Risk Measurement**: Deterministic models cannot quantify the distribution of possible outcomes\n",
        "\n",
        "### Stochastic Interest Rate Models\n",
        "\n",
        "**Stochastic models** treat interest rates as random variables that evolve over time. They model the short-term risk-free rate $r_t$ as a process governed by:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$dr_t = \\mu(r_t, t) dt + \\sigma(r_t, t) dW_t$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Where:\n",
        "- $dr_t$ = Change in the short rate\n",
        "- $\\mu(r_t, t)$ = **Drift** (deterministic component—expected direction)\n",
        "- $\\sigma(r_t, t)$ = **Volatility** (randomness magnitude)\n",
        "- $dW_t$ = **Wiener process increment** (random shock)\n",
        "\n",
        "### Popular Stochastic Models Hierarchy\n",
        "\n",
        "```\n",
        "├── Vasicek Model (1977) - Gaussian, mean-reverting\n",
        "├── CIR Model (1985) - Positive rates, mean-reverting\n",
        "├── Dothan Model (1978) - Geometric Brownian motion\n",
        "├── Black-Derman-Toy (1990) - Calibrated to yield curve\n",
        "└── Hull-White (1990) - Extended Vasicek with time-varying parameters\n",
        "```\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Dothan Model: Introduction\n",
        "\n",
        "The **Dothan model**, introduced by Michael U. Dothan in 1978, is one of the earliest and most elegant stochastic interest rate models.\n",
        "\n",
        "### Key Features\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Geometric Brownian Motion**: The short rate follows the same type of process as stock prices:\n",
        "   $$dr_t = \\mu r_t dt + \\sigma r_t dW_t$$\n",
        "\n",
        "2. **Intuitive Parameters**:\n",
        "   - $\\mu$: Expected percentage drift (e.g., 2% per year)\n",
        "   - $\\sigma$: Volatility (e.g., 15% per year)\n",
        "\n",
        "3. **Positive Rates** (under typical parameterizations): Since rates follow GBM, they remain positive\n",
        "\n",
        "4. **Simplicity**: Closed-form solutions exist for zero-coupon bond prices, making it tractable for analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "### Why Study the Dothan Model?\n",
        "\n",
        ":::{.callout-info}\n",
        "## Educational Value\n",
        "\n",
        "The Dothan model provides:\n",
        "- **Classic Foundation**: Historical importance in the development of interest rate modeling\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Analytical Tractability**: Allows detailed theoretical analysis\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Practical Insights**: Demonstrates how rate uncertainty propagates to bond valuations\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Simulation Foundation**: Easy to implement and extend for student projects\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "### Applications in Risk Management\n",
        "\n",
        "Understanding how the Dothan model works enables practitioners to:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Measure Interest Rate Risk**: Quantify potential losses from rate movements\n",
        "- **Price Derivatives**: Value interest rate options and complex securities\n",
        "- **Manage Portfolios**: Optimize hedge ratios and duration matching\n",
        "- **Stress Test**: Assess portfolio resilience to extreme rate scenarios\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "## Project Overview\n",
        "\n",
        "This project guides you through:\n",
        "\n",
        "1. **Learning** how the Dothan model works mathematically\n",
        "2. **Simulating** realistic interest rate paths under the model\n",
        "3. **Pricing** zero-coupon bonds using Monte Carlo methods\n",
        "4. **Analyzing** how bond prices respond to changes in parameters\n",
        "5. **Managing** interest rate risk in a fixed-income portfolio\n",
        "6. **Visualizing** results with professional graphics"
      ],
